Adelani Adepegba, Abuja A Police Special Forces operative, Inspector Muhammed Abubakar, has died following the injuries he sustained during the counter-insurgency operation at Kuduru Forest in Kaduna State on Wednesday. Thirteen other officers, comprising two Superintendents of Police, one DSP, four Inspectors and six Sergeants, including the pilot and co-pilot of the police helicopter, also sustained varying degrees of injury and were said to be receiving treatment. The police spokesman, DCP Frank Mba, on Thursday, said the Special Forces arrested a wanted notorious cattle rustler, Haruna Basullube, and critically injured a Boko Haram commander, Mallam Abba, during the operation where 250 criminals were killed. The force explained that a notorious kidnapper, simply identified as Mofa, was also wounded during the raid on the camp of the Ansaru terrorist group. The statement read, “In the aftermath of the police counter-terrorism operations which successfully neutralised the operational bases of the Ansaru terrorists group and bandits, one Haruna Basullube, one of the most wanted kidnappers/cattle rustlers in the country and one Bashir Leta, another notorious bandits’ commander were killed; while one Mallam Abba, Commander of Boko Haram camp in Kuduru Forest and one Mofa, a notorious kidnapper, were critically injured.“ The police asked citizens living in the Birnin-Gwari area of Kaduna State to be on the lookout for fleeing bandits, especially those with bullet wounds and report every suspicious behaviour to the police. Copyright PUNCH.
